P&O is the most widely used MPPT method at present. Its basic principle is to apply a positive disturbance voltage to the fuel cell, sample its output voltage and current, and calculate the change rate of its voltage and power. If the output power increases after the disturbance, it indicates that the direction of the disturbance voltage is the direction of the increase of the power output, and the disturbance should be continued in this direction; otherwise, the disturbance should be in the opposite direction. According to the changing direction of voltage and power, the disturbance voltage is continuously applied to the fuel cell until the maximum output power is approached gradually, so as to realize the MPPT. The flowchart of P&O algorithm is shown in Fig. 3, in which “k” denotes the sampling point, Δd\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta d$$\end{document} stands for the increment of duty cycle.Figure 3
Flow chart of P&O algorithm of MFC.

